> Take a trip to Southern India with this mouthwatering shrimp stew! Creamy coconut milk is infused with rich aromas from curry, tomatoes, onions, and garam masala, making this a decadent dish. These flavors will transport you to the tranquil backwaters of Kerala where the cuisine is as colorful as the region.

Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and chop the @Red Onion{1}(halved, peeled, and chopped). Mince or grate the @Garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Finely chop the @Cilantro{¼%ounce}(chopped, reserving a few leaves for garnish). Chop the @Jalapeño{1}(chopped), removing the ribs and seeds if you prefer less heat.

In a #small pot{}, bring @water{1%cup} and a large pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil. Once boiling, add the @Basmati Rice{½%cup}, cover, and reduce to a low simmer for ~{15-20%minutes}, until tender.

Heat a large drizzle of @Olive Oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add the @Mustard Seeds{1%teaspoon} and cook until fragrant, for about ~{1%minute}. Add the @Curry Powder{1%teaspoon}, @Turmeric{1%teaspoon}, jalapeño pepper, and onions and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} until slightly browned. Add the garlic and cilantro and cook for an additional ~{30%seconds} until fragrant. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Add in the @Crushed Tomatoes{1%box}, half the @Coconut Milk{1/2%can}, @water{1%cup}, and a pinch of @Cayenne Pepper{1%pinch}. Season with salt and pepper, then bring to a boil.

Add the @Shrimp{10%ounce} to the #pan{} and reduce the heat to low. Cook for ~{4-5%minutes}, until the shrimp are opaque and cooked through. Season to taste with salt, pepper, and additional cayenne, if desired.

Stir the @Garam Masala{1%teaspoon} into the pan and remove from the heat. Serve the South Indian shrimp curry on a bed of basmati rice and garnish with the cilantro leaves. Enjoy!